<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-797-836  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 797 836.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 27 1990 v24 n35 p68(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's missing from lights-out?: tools have made strides, butexpert systems, novel approaches still lacking.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robins, Gary.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many data center managers are moving towards lights-outoperations, but the degree to which it can be achieved isuncertain.andP;  Credit Agricole's operations are 75 percent unattendedand the company hopes to achieve 95 percent automation.andO;Automation tools have been greatly improved during the late1980's, but they must advance yet further if lights-out operationsare to be fully realized.andP;  The ideal system would be able todetect problems and correct them all by itself.andP;  Consoleautomation tools must have their own expert systems to accomplishthis.andP;  Tasks such as the mounting and dismounting of tapes, backupprocedures, report distribution and maintenance may neveradequately lend themselves to automation.andP;  However, the questionremains as to whether data center managers truly want completelyautomated operations.andP;  Some degree of human intervention is oftendesirable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information CentersAutomationManagement StyleMaintenanceHuman FactorsCost Benefit AnalysisExpert Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>